¬ß Why ‚¶â
¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ We speak of objects which we can add and scale. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Of course, our model is the real vectors. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬ß Definition ‚¶â
¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ A ‚ù¨vector space‚ù≠ (or ‚ù¨linear space‚ù≠, or ‚ù¨linear class‚ù≠) is
    an ordered triple consisting of (1) a commutative group, (2)
    a field, and (3) a function from the product of the field
    ground set and group ground set to the group ground set. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ We call the ground set of the commutative group the
    ‚ù¨vectors‚ù≠ and we call the group operation ‚ù¨vector addition‚ù≠. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We call the field the ‚ù¨scalars‚ù≠. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ The field has addition and multiplication of scalars which
    we call ‚ù¨scalar addition‚ù≠ and ‚ù¨scalar multiplication‚ù≠,
    respectively. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ The ‚ù¨scaling map‚ù≠ is the map on pairs of scalars and
    vectors. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ The first property is that the result of scaling a vector
    by a scalar, and then scaling the result by a second scalar
    is the same as first multiplying the scalars and then
    scaling the vector. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ The second property is that the result of scaling a vector
    by the scalar sum of two scalars is the same as scaling
    the vector by each scalar separately and then adding the
    vectors. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ The third property is that the result of scaling the vector
    sum of two vectors is the same as scaling each individually
    and then adding the two vectors. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬ß¬ß Notation ‚¶â
¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ Let $(V,+)$ be a commutative group and $(F, \tilde{+},
    \cdot)$ be a field. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Let $s: F √ó V ‚Üí V$. $((V, +), (F, \tilde{+}, \cdot), s)$
    is a vector space if ‚¶â
  ùç´ ‚¶ä
    ‚Ä£ $s(b,s(a, v)) = s(b \cdot a, v)$ for all $a, b ‚àà F$
      and $v ‚àà V$. ‚¶â

    ‚Ä£ $s(a\tilde{+}b, v) = s(a, v) + s(b, v)$ for all $a, b ‚àà
      F$ and $v ‚àà V$. ‚¶â

    ‚Ä£ $s(a, u + v) = s(a,u) + s(a, b)$ for all $a ‚àà F$ and
      $u, v ‚àà V$. ‚¶â
  ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ We can simplify (contract) the notation above with four
    conventions. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ First, we denote both vector and scalar addition by $+$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ So $a + b$ denotes $a \tilde{+} b$ for all $a, b ‚àà F$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Second, we contract $¬∑$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ So $ab$ denotes $a ¬∑ b$ for all $a, b ‚àà F$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Third, we contract the scaling map. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ So $av$ denotes $s(a, v)$ for $a ‚àà F$ and $v ‚àà V$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Fourth, we conventionally take the scaling map to have
    precedence so that $au + av$ means $(au) + (av)$ for all
    $a ‚àà F$ and $u,v ‚àà V$. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ We denote: ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ (1) ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ $b(av) = (ba)v$; ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ (2) ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ $(a+b)v = av + bv$; ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ and (3) ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ $a(u + v) = au + av$ ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ for all ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ $a,b ‚àà F$ and $u, v ‚àà V$. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ Finally, we say: let $(V, F)$ be a vector space, assuming
    the above notational conventions. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Sometimes we will say let $V$ be a vector space over the
    field $F$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Often the field will be assumed, in which case we will
    refer to the vector space $V$ and define functions on $V$. ‚¶â
‚¶â
